verbatimLocality: Ozark-St. Francis National Forests, Pettigrew, AR, US

associatedTaxa: Growing with Heuchera parviflora var. puberula (see Witsell 11-0254).
occurrenceRemarks: Scattered to locally common on cliff face.
habitat: NW-facing bluff (Everton Formation & St. Peter Sandstone) with both acidic and calcareous influence. It is very uncommon to see H. parviflora puberula (generally a calciphile) and H. villosa arkansana (generally an acidiphile) on the same bluff.
locality: Ozark Highlands. Dissected Springfield Plateau-Elk River Hills Ecoregion. USGS Eula 7.5' Quad. Gene Rush Wildlife Management Area. S side of Cave Creek, E of linear, streamside field N of CR 252, 0.3 mi. E of low water bridge. This is on the outside of a bend where the creek turns northward.
locationRemarks: Vicinity of coordinates; coordinates not obtained in situ with GPS but estimated post-collection event using mapping programs. Coordinates considered accurate to within 100 m.

occurrenceRemarks: Hundreds of clumps in cracks and pockets in bluff.
habitat: Mesic NE-facing sandstone bluffs.
locality: Boston Mountains. Upper Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Weathers 7.5' Quad. 3.6 mi. NNE of Boston. Kings River Natural Area. Along Mink Creek near confluence with Kings River.

occurrenceRemarks: Hundreds of clumps in cracks and pockets in bluff.
habitat: Mesic NE-facing sandstone bluffs.
locality: Boston Mountains. Upper Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Weathers 7.5' Quad. 3.6 mi. NNE of Boston. Kings River Natural Area. Along Mink Creek near confluence with Kings River.

occurrenceRemarks: Locally common in cracks and pits in the rock. Population certainly extends down bluffline to the S into Benton County.; Fresh flowers white.
habitat: E-facing sandstone bluff (mapped as either the Wedington Member of the Fayetteville Shale or the Batesville Sandstone).
locality: Ozark Highlands. Dissected Springfield Plateau-Elk River Hills Ecoregion. USGS Rhea 7.5' Quad. Ozark National Forest. Wedington Mountain. W of Lookout Tower Rd. (CR 849), 0.5 mi. N of Hwy 16. Just (a few feet) inside Washington County according to Google Earth.

associatedTaxa: Growing with Dryopteris marginalis, Hydrangea arborescens, Vitis aestivalis, Dennstaedtia punctilobula, etc.
occurrenceRemarks: 100-200 plants scattered on lower portions of large sandstone blocks, often growing from cracks or pits in vertical cliff faces.
habitat: Sandstone bluff on N side of large, free-standing sandstone block sitting on N-facing hillside.
locality: Boston Mountains. Lower Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Concord 7.5' Quad. 4.5 mi. W of Locust Grove & 0.65 mi. SSSE of top of Round Mountain. Hall property.
locationRemarks: Vicinity of coordinates; coordinates not obtained in situ with GPS but estimated post-collection event using mapping programs. Coordinates considered accurate to within 100 m.

occurrenceRemarks: Locally common, growing from cracks in bluffs.
habitat: E-facing sandstone bluffs below trail and overlook.
locality: Arkansas Valley. Arkansas Valley Hills Ecoregion. USGS Damascus 7.5' Quad. Cove Creek Natural Area. W of Cove Creek.

associatedTaxa: Growing with Philadelphus pubescens, P. hirsutus, Muhlenbergia sp., etc.
occurrenceRemarks: Scattered to locally common on ledges and pockets in low bluffs.
habitat: N-facing shale and sandstone bluff.
locality: Boston Mountains. Lower Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Treat 7.5' Quad. Ozark National Forest. Long Pool Recreation Area. S side of Big Piney River, E of campgrounds.
locationRemarks: Vicinity of coordinates; coordinates not obtained in situ with GPS but estimated post-collection event using mapping programs. Coordinates considered accurate to within 100 m.

associatedTaxa: Growing with Philadelphus pubescens, Styaphylea trifolia, Toxicodendron radicans, Acer saccharum, Dryopteris marginalis, Polymnia canadensis, Polystichum acrostichoides, Liquidambar styraciflua, Carya cordiformis & Ostrya virginiana.
occurrenceRemarks: 100+ plants observed among mossy sandstone bluff and boulders.
habitat: Rich, mesic, NW-facing mid-slope, at base of steep sandstone bluff.
locality: Boston Mountains. Lower Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Rex 7.5' Quad. Gulf Mountain Wildlife Management Area. Along S side of South Fork Little Red River, about 0.55 mi. upstream of Cottonwood Drive crossing. TRS: T11N R16W S26 near Center W2

recordedBy: Theo Witsell; Mary Alice Beer, Eric Sundell et al.
habitat: Rich, mossy, north-facing bluff. Geology = Bloyd Shale & Prairie Grove Member of Hale Formation.
locality: Boston Mountains. Lower Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Parma 7.5' Quad. At mouth of Deadland Hollow above Sandiff Road and arm of Greers Ferry Lake (North Fork of the Little Red River). TRS: T12N R12W S27 NE4SE4
locationRemarks: Vicinity of coordinates; coordinates not obtained in situ with GPS but estimated post-collection event using mapping programs. Coordinates considered accurate to within 100 m.

associatedTaxa: Growing with liverworts, mosses, Solidago caesia, Hydrangea arborescens & Toxicodendron radicans, with Philadelphus hirsutus on drier bluff and scree nearby.
occurrenceRemarks: About 50+ plants observed along about 8 m.
habitat: Short, mesic (dripping in spots) NW-facing shale and sandstone bluff just above stream channel.
locality: Boston Mountains. Lower Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Sand Gap 7.5' Quad. Ozark National Forest. About 6.7 air mi. SSW of Sand Gap. Along Indian Creek, just E of Indian Creek Rd. (Forest Service Rd. 1808) about 1.7 rd. mi. N of jct. with Treat Rd. TRS: T11N R20W S4 SW4SW4SE4

associatedTaxa: Growing with liverworts, Hydrangea arborescens, Toxicodendron radicans, Carex sp., Muhlenbergia sp., Solidago caesia, Boehmeria cylindrica & Amphicarpaea bracteata.
occurrenceRemarks: 25+ plants observed in bloom along about 70 m of bluff.; Fresh flowers white.
habitat: Short, moist, east-facing, sandstone bluff above stream bank.
locality: Boston Mountains. Lower Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Sand Gap 7.5' Quad. Ozark National Forest. West bank of North Fork Illinois Bayou, immediately upstream of Victor Rd. (Forest Service Rd. 1000) crossing near the old community of Victor, about 4.6 mi. E of jct. with AR Hwy 7, S of Sand Gap. TRS: T12N R19W S34 NW4NW4

associatedTaxa: Growing with mosses, Toxicodendron radicans & Asplenium rhizophyllum.
occurrenceRemarks: Locally common, hundreds of plants observed.; Many immature. In bud.
habitat: Mesic, shaded, lower W-facing sandstone bluffs just above stream terrace.
locality: Boston Mountains. Lower Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Simpson 7.5' Quad. Ozark National Forest. About 4.1 air mi. NW of Hector. E of North Fork Illinois Bayou and about 0.2 air mi. W of North Fork Rd. (Forest Service Rd. 1310) at a point about 0.96 rd. mi. N of jct. with Granny Gap Rd. (Forest Service Rd. 1001). TRS: T10N R19W S16 E2SW4

associatedTaxa: Growing with Sedum ternatum, Elymus hystrix, Aquilegia canadensis, mosses, Polymnia canadensis, Hydrangea arborescens, Toxicodendron radicans, Physocarpus opulifolius, Parthenocissus quinquefolia, etc.
occurrenceRemarks: Locally common, about 100+ plants observed, about 40 of which mature, along about 20 m. About 30+ plants also observed about 0.2 stream mi. upstream.; Flowers in bud.
habitat: Mesic sandstone bluffs and ledges along and above stream channel.
locality: Boston Mountains. Upper Boston Mountains Ecoregion. USGS Weathers 7.5' Quad. Kings River Falls Natural Area. Along Kings River about 0.5 stream mi. downstream of the Falls, or about 1.3 stream mi. downstream of Madison Co. Rd. 3500 crossing. N of Boston and SE of Venus. TRS: T14N R24W S6 NW4
